[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Erase the overlapping edges of the two paths found, and reverse the direction of the remaining arcs on the first shortest path such that each arc on it is directed towards the destination vertex now.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] In lieu of the general purpose Ford's shortest path algorithm valid for negative arcs present anywhere in a graph (with nonexistent negative cycles), Bhandari provides two different algorithms, either one of which can be used in Step 4.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] One algorithm is a slight modification of the traditional Dijkstra's algorithm, and the other called the Breadth-First-Search (BFS) algorithm is a variant of the Moore's algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Because the negative arcs are only on the first shortest path, no negative cycle arises in the transformed graph (Steps 2 and 3).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] In a nonnegative graph, the modified Dijkstra algorithm reduces to the traditional Dijkstra's algorithm, and can therefore be used in Step 1 of the above algorithm (and similarly, the BFS algorithm).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] G = (V, E) d(i) – the distance of vertex i (i∈V) from source vertex A; it is the sum of arcs in a possible path from vertex A to vertex i.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Note that d(A)=0; P(i) – the predecessor of vertex i on the same path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Figure A shows the given undirected graph G(V, E) with edge weights.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Figure B displays the calculated shortest path ABCZ from A to Z (in bold lines).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Figure C shows the reversal of the arcs of the shortest path and their negative weights.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Figure D displays the shortest path ADCBZ from A to Z determined in the new transformed. graph of Figure C (this is determined using the modified Dijkstra algorithm (or the BFS algorithm) valid for such negative arcs; there are never any negative cycles in such a transformed graph).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Figure E displays the determined shortest path ADCBZ in the original graph.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Figure F displays the determined shortest pair of edge-disjoint paths (ABZ, ADCZ) found after erasing the edge BC common to paths ABCZ and ADCBZ, and grouping the remaining edges suitably.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] In a nonnegative graph, the modified Dijkstra algorithm functions as the traditional Dijkstra algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] In a graph characterized by vertices with degrees of O(d) (d<|V|), the efficiency is O(d|V|), being O(|V|2), in the worst case, as in the traditional Dijkstra's case.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] In the transformed graph of the edge disjoint shortest pair algorithm, which contains negative arcs, a given vertex previously "permanently" labeled in Step 2a of the modified Dijkstra algorithm may be revisited and relabeled in Step 3a, and inserted back in vertex set S (Step 3b).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] The efficiency of the modified Dijkstra in such a transformed graph becomes O(d2|V|), being O(|V|3) in the worst case.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] Most graphs of practical interest are usually sparse, possessing vertex degrees of O(1), in which case the efficiency of the modified Dijkstra algorithm applied to the transformed graph becomes O(|V|) (or, equivalently, O(|E|)).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] The reweighting requires building the entire shortest path tree rooted at the source vertex.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] By circumventing this additional graph transformation, and using the modified Dijkstra algorithm instead, Bhandari's approach results in a simplified version of the edge disjoint shortest pair algorithm without sacrificing much in efficiency at least for sparse graphs.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/edge-disjoint-shortest-pair-algorithm] The algorithms presented for undirected graphs also extend to directed graphs, and apply in general to any problem (in any technical discipline) that can be modeled as a graph of vertices and edges (or arcs).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In graph theory, a **flow network** (also known as a **transportation network**) is a directed graph where each edge has a **capacity** and each edge receives a flow.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The amount of flow on an edge cannot exceed the capacity of the edge.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Often in operations research, a directed graph is called a **network**, the vertices are called **nodes** and the edges are called **arcs**.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] A flow must satisfy the restriction that the amount of flow into a node equals the amount of flow out of it, unless it is a **source**, which has only outgoing flow, or **sink**, which has only incoming flow.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] A flow network can be used to model traffic in a computer network, circulation with demands, fluids in pipes, currents in an electrical circuit, or anything similar in which something travels through a network of nodes.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] As such, efficient algorithms for solving network flows can also be applied to solve problems that can be reduced to a flow network, including survey design, airline scheduling, image segmentation, and the matching problem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] A **network** is a directed graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with a non-negative **capacity** function *c* for each edge, and without multiple arcs (i.e. edges with the same source and target nodes).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Without loss of generality, we may assume that if (*u*, *v*) ∈ *E*, then (*v*, *u*) is also a member of E.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] If two nodes in G are distinguished – one as the source s and the other as the sink t – then (*G*, *c*, *s*, *t*) is called a **flow network**.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In flow networks, the source s is deficient, and the sink t is active.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Pseudo-flows, feasible flows, and pre-flows are all examples of flow functions.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The **value** |*f*| of a feasible flow f for a network, is the net flow into the sink t of the flow network, that is: |*f*| = *x**f* (*t*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Note, the flow value in a network is also equal to the total outgoing flow of source s, that is: |*f*| = −*x**f* (*s*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Also, if we define *A* as a set of nodes in *G* such that *s* ∈ *A* and *t* ∉ *A*, the flow value is equal to the total net flow going out of A (i.e. |*f*| = *f* out(*A*) − *f* in(*A*)).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The flow value in a network is the total amount of flow from s to t.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a process of breaking down a given flow into a collection of path flows and cycle flows.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Every flow through a network can be decomposed into one or more paths and corresponding quantities, such that each edge in the flow equals the sum of all quantities of paths that pass through it.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a powerful tool in optimization problems to maximize or minimize specific flow parameters.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] We do not use multiple arcs within a network because we can combine those arcs into a single arc.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Along with the other constraints, the skew symmetry constraint must be remembered during this step to maintain the direction of the original pseudo-flow arc.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Adding flow to an arc is the same as adding an arc with the capacity of zero.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The **residual capacity** of an arc e with respect to a pseudo-flow f is denoted *c**f*, and it is the difference between the arc's capacity and its flow.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] From this we can construct a **residual network**, denoted *G**f* (*V*, *E**f*), with a capacity function *c**f* which models the amount of *available* capacity on the set of arcs in *G* = (*V*, *E*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] More specifically, capacity function *c**f* of each arc (*u*, *v*) in the residual network represents the amount of flow which can be transferred from u to v given the current state of the flow within the network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] This concept is used in Ford–Fulkerson algorithm which computes the maximum flow in a flow network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Note that there can be an unsaturated path (a path with available capacity) from u to v in the residual network, even though there is no such path from u to v in the original network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Since flows in opposite directions cancel out, *decreasing* the flow from v to u is the same as *increasing* the flow from u to v.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] More simply, an augmenting path is an available flow path from the source to the sink.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] A network is at maximum flow if and only if there is no augmenting path in the residual network *G**f*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The **bottleneck** is the minimum residual capacity of all the edges in a given augmenting path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] See example explained in the "Example" section of this article.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The flow network is at maximum flow if and only if it has a bottleneck with a value equal to zero.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] If any augmenting path exists, its bottleneck weight will be greater than 0.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In other words, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then there is an augmenting path from the source to the sink.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] However, we know that if there is any augmenting path, then the network is not at maximum flow, which in turn means that, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then the network is not at maximum flow.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The term "augmenting the flow" for an augmenting path means updating the flow f of each arc in this augmenting path to equal the capacity *c* of the bottleneck.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Augmenting the flow corresponds to pushing additional flow along the augmenting path until there is no remaining available residual capacity in the bottleneck.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Sometimes, when modeling a network with more than one source, a **supersource** is introduced to the graph.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] This consists of a vertex connected to each of the sources with edges of infinite capacity, so as to act as a global source.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] A similar construct for sinks is called a **supersink**.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In Figure 1 you see a flow network with source labeled s, sink t, and four additional nodes.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The flow and capacity is denoted $f/c$ .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Notice how the network upholds the capacity constraint and flow conservation constraint.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The total amount of flow from s to t is 5, which can be easily seen from the fact that the total outgoing flow from s is 5, which is also the incoming flow to t.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] By the skew symmetry constraint, from c to a is -2 because the flow from a to c is 2.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In Figure 2 you see the residual network for the same given flow.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Notice how there is positive residual capacity on some edges where the original capacity is zero in Figure 1, for example for the edge $(d,c)$ .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] There is available capacity along the paths $(s,a,c,t)$ , $(s,a,b,d,t)$ and $(s,a,b,d,c,t)$ , which are then the augmenting paths.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Picture a series of water pipes, fitting into a network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Each pipe is of a certain diameter, so it can only maintain a flow of a certain amount of water.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Anywhere that pipes meet, the total amount of water coming into that junction must be equal to the amount going out, otherwise we would quickly run out of water, or we would have a buildup of water.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] We have a water inlet, which is the source, and an outlet, the sink.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] A flow would then be one possible way for water to get from source to sink so that the total amount of water coming out of the outlet is consistent.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Intuitively, the total flow of a network is the rate at which water comes out of the outlet.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Flows can pertain to people or material over transportation networks, or to electricity over electrical distribution systems.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] For any such physical network, the flow coming into any intermediate node needs to equal the flow going out of that node.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] This conservation constraint is equivalent to Kirchhoff's current law.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Flow networks also find applications in ecology: flow networks arise naturally when considering the flow of nutrients and energy between different organisms in a food web.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The mathematical problems associated with such networks are quite different from those that arise in networks of fluid or traffic flow.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The field of ecosystem network analysis, developed by Robert Ulanowicz and others, involves using concepts from information theory and thermodynamics to study the evolution of these networks over time.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The simplest and most common problem using flow networks is to find what is called the maximum flow, which provides the largest possible total flow from the source to the sink in a given graph.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] There are many other problems which can be solved using max flow algorithms, if they are appropriately modeled as flow networks, such as bipartite matching, the assignment problem and the transportation problem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Maximum flow problems can be solved in polynomial time with various algorithms (see table).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The max-flow min-cut theorem states that finding a maximal network flow is equivalent to finding a cut of minimum capacity that separates the source and the sink, where a cut is the division of vertices such that the source is in one division and the sink is in another.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In a multi-commodity flow problem, you have multiple sources and sinks, and various "commodities" which are to flow from a given source to a given sink.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] This could be for example various goods that are produced at various factories, and are to be delivered to various given customers through the *same* transportation network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In a minimum cost flow problem, each edge $u,v$ has a given cost $k(u,v)$ , and the cost of sending the flow $f(u,v)$ across the edge is $f(u,v)\cdot k(u,v)$ .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The objective is to send a given amount of flow from the source to the sink, at the lowest possible price.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In a circulation problem, you have a lower bound $\ell (u,v)$ on the edges, in addition to the upper bound $c(u,v)$ .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] Often, flow conservation holds for *all* nodes in a circulation problem, and there is a connection from the sink back to the source.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In this way, you can dictate the total flow with $\ell (t,s)$ and $c(t,s)$ .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] The flow *circulates* through the network, hence the name of the problem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In a **network with gains** or **generalized network** each edge has a **gain**, a real number (not zero) such that, if the edge has gain *g*, and an amount *x* flows into the edge at its tail, then an amount *gx* flows out at the head.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] In a **source localization problem**, an algorithm tries to identify the most likely source node of information diffusion through a partially observed network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/flow-network] This can be done in linear time for trees and cubic time for arbitrary networks and has applications ranging from tracking mobile phone users to identifying the originating source of disease outbreaks.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] The ***k* shortest path routing** problem is a generalization of the shortest path routing problem in a given network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] It asks not only about a shortest path but also about next *k−1* shortest paths (which may be longer than the shortest path).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] A variation of the problem is the loopless *k* shortest paths.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Finding *k* shortest paths is possible by extending Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman-Ford algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Since 1957, many papers have been published on the *k* shortest path routing problem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Most of the fundamental works were done between 1960s and 2001.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Since then, most of the research has been on the problem's applications and its variants.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In 2010, Michael Günther et al. published a book on *Symbolic calculation of*k*-shortest paths and related measures with the stochastic process algebra tool CASPA*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Dijkstra's algorithm can be generalized to find the *k* shortest paths.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] There are two main variations of the *k* shortest path routing problem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In one variation, paths are allowed to visit the same node more than once, thus creating loops.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In another variation, paths are required to be simple and loopless.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] The loopy version is solvable using Eppstein's algorithm and the loopless variation is solvable by Yen's algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In this variant, the problem is simplified by not requiring paths to be loopless.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Fox in 1975 in which the *k*-shortest paths are determined in *O*(*m* + *kn* log *n*) asymptotic time complexity (using big *O* notation).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In 1998, David Eppstein reported an approach that maintains an asymptotic complexity of *O*(*m* + *n* log *n* + *k*) by computing an implicit representation of the paths, each of which can be output in *O*(*n*) extra time.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In 2015, Akiba *et al.* devised an indexing method as a significantly faster alternative for Eppstein's algorithm, in which a data structure called an index is constructed from a graph and then top-*k* distances between arbitrary pairs of vertices can be rapidly obtained.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In the loopless variant, the paths are forbidden to contain loops, which adds an additional level of complexity.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] It can be solved using Yen's algorithm to find the lengths of all shortest paths from a fixed node to all other nodes in an *n*-node non negative-distance network, a technique requiring only 2*n*2 additions and *n*2 comparison, fewer than other available shortest path algorithms need.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] The running time complexity is pseudo-polynomial, being *O*(*kn*(*m* + *n* log *n*)) (where *m* and *n* represent the number of edges and vertices, respectively).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In 2007, John Hershberger and Subhash Suri proposed a replacement paths algorithm, a more efficient implementation of Lawler's and Yen's algorithm with *O*(*n*) improvement in time for a large number of graphs, but not all of them (therefore not changing the asymptotic bound of Yen's algorithm).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] The following example makes use of Yen's model to find *k* shortest paths between communicating end nodes.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] That is, it finds a shortest path, second shortest path, etc. up to the Kth shortest path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Another example is the use of *k* shortest paths algorithm to track multiple objects.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] The technique implements a multiple object tracker based on the *k* shortest paths routing algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] A set of probabilistic occupancy maps is used as input.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] The complete details can be found at "Computer Vision Laboratory – CVLAB".
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Another use of *k* shortest paths algorithms is to design a transit network that enhances passengers' experience in public transportation systems.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Such an example of a transit network can be constructed by putting traveling time under consideration.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] In addition to traveling time, other conditions may be taken depending upon economical and geographical limitations.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Despite variations in parameters, the *k* shortest path algorithms finds the most optimal solutions that satisfies almost all user needs.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Such applications of *k* shortest path algorithms are becoming common, recently Xu, He, Song, and Chaudhry (2012) studied the *k* shortest path problems in transit network systems.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/k-shortest-path-routing] Cherkassky et al. provide more algorithms and associated evaluations.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] In the mathematical discipline of graph theory, **Menger's theorem** says that in a finite graph, the size of a minimum cut set is equal to the maximum number of disjoint paths that can be found between any pair of vertices.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Proved by Karl Menger in 1927, it characterizes the connectivity of a graph.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] It is generalized by the max-flow min-cut theorem, which is a weighted, edge version, and which in turn is a special case of the strong duality theorem for linear programs.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] All these statements in both edge and vertex versions remain true in directed graphs (when considering directed paths).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Most direct proofs consider a more general statement to allow proving it by induction.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] It is also convenient to use definitions that include some degenerate cases.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] The following proof for undirected graphs works without change for directed graphs or multi-graphs, provided we take *path* to mean directed path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] For sets of vertices *A,B ⊂ G* (not necessarily disjoint), an *AB-path* is a path in *G* with a starting vertex in *A*, a final vertex in *B*, and no internal vertices either in *A* or in *B*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] We allow a path with a single vertex in *A ∩ B* and zero edges.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] An *AB-separator* of size *k* is a set *S* of *k* vertices (which may intersect *A* and *B*) such that *G−S* contains no *AB*-path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] An *AB-connector* of size *k* is a union of *k* vertex-disjoint *AB*-paths.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] In other words, if no *k*−1 vertices disconnect *A* from *B*, then there exist *k* disjoint paths from *A* to *B*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] This variant implies the above vertex-connectivity statement: for *x,y ∈ G* in the previous section, apply the current theorem to *G*−{*x,y*} with *A = N(x)*, *B = N(y)*, the neighboring vertices of *x,y*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Then a set of vertices disconnecting *x* and *y* is the same thing as an *AB*-separator, and removing the end vertices in a set of independent *xy*-paths gives an *AB*-connector.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] For *G* having an edge *e*, we may assume by induction that the Theorem holds for *G−e*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] If *G−e* has a minimal *AB*-separator of size *k*, then there is an *AB*-connector of size *k* in *G−e*, and hence in *G*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Otherwise, let *S* be a *AB*-separator of *G−e* of size less than *k*, so that every *AB*-path in *G* contains a vertex of *S* or the edge *e*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] The size of *S* must be *k-1*, since if it was less, *S* together with either endpoint of *e* would be a better *AB*-separator of *G*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] In *G−S* there is an *AB*-path through *e*, since *S* alone is too small to be an *AB*-separator of *G*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Let *v1* be the earlier and *v2* be the later vertex of *e* on such a path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Then *v1* is reachable from *A* but not from *B* in *G−S−e*, while *v2* is reachable from *B* but not from *A*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Now, let *S1 = S ∪ {v1}*, and consider a minimum *AS1*-separator *T* in *G−e*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Since *v2* is not reachable from *A* in *G−S1*, *T* is also an *AS1*-separator in *G*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Then *T* is also an *AB*-separator in *G* (because every *AB*-path intersects *S1*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] By induction, *G−e* contains an *AS1*-connector *C1* of size *k*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Because of its size, the endpoints of the paths in it must be exactly *S1*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Similarly, letting *S2 = S ∪ {v2}*, a minimum *S2B*-separator has size *k*, and there is an *S2B*-connector *C2* of size *k*, with paths whose starting points are exactly *S2*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Furthermore, since *S1* disconnects *G*, every path in *C1* is internally disjoint from every path in *C2*, and we can define an *AB*-connector of size *k* in *G* by concatenating paths (*k−1* paths through *S* and one path going through *e=v1v2*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] The directed edge version of the theorem easily implies the other versions.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] To infer the directed graph vertex version, it suffices to split each vertex *v* into two vertices *v1*, *v2*, with all ingoing edges going to *v1*, all outgoing edges going from *v2*, and an additional edge from *v1* to *v2*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] The directed versions of the theorem immediately imply undirected versions: it suffices to replace each edge of an undirected graph with a pair of directed edges (a digon).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] The directed edge version in turn follows from its weighted variant, the max-flow min-cut theorem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Its proofs are often correctness proofs for max flow algorithms.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] It is also a special case of the still more general (strong) duality theorem for linear programs.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] In this version the theorem follows in fairly easily from Kőnig's theorem: in a bipartite graph, the minimal size of a cover is equal to the maximal size of a matching.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] This is done as follows: replace every vertex *v* in the original digraph *D* by two vertices *v'*, *v''*, and every edge *uv* by the edge *u'v''*; additionally, include the edges *v'v''* for every vertex *v* that is neither in *A* nor *B*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] This results in a bipartite graph, whose one side consists of the vertices *v'*, and the other of the vertices *v''*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Applying Kőnig's theorem we obtain a matching *M* and a cover *C* of the same size.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] In particular, exactly one endpoint of each edge of *M* is in *C*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Add to *C* all vertices *a''*, for *a* in *A,* and all vertices *b'*, for *b* in *B*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Let *P* be the set of all *AB*-paths composed of edges *uv* in *D* such that *u'v''* belongs to M.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Let *Q* in the original graph consist of all vertices *v* such that both *v'* and *v''* belong to *C*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] It is straightforward to check that *Q* is an *AB*-separating set, that every path in the family *P* contains precisely one vertex from *Q*, and every vertex in *Q* lies on a path from *P*, as desired.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] Menger's theorem holds for infinite graphs, and in that context it applies to the minimum cut between any two elements that are either vertices or ends of the graph (Halin 1974).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] The following result of Ron Aharoni and Eli Berger was originally a conjecture proposed by Paul Erdős, and before being proved was known as the **Erdős–Menger conjecture**.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/menger-s-theorem] It is equivalent to Menger's theorem when the graph is finite.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] In graph theory, the **shortest path problem** is the problem of finding a path between two vertices (or nodes) in a graph such that the sum of the weights of its constituent edges is minimized.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the shortest path between two intersections on a road map may be modeled as a special case of the shortest path problem in graphs, where the vertices correspond to intersections and the edges correspond to road segments, each weighted by the length or distance of each segment.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The shortest path problem can be defined for graphs whether undirected, directed, or mixed.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The definition for undirected graphs states that every edge can be traversed in either direction.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Directed graphs require that consecutive vertices be connected by an appropriate directed edge.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Two vertices are adjacent when they are both incident to a common edge.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] A path in an undirected graph is a sequence of vertices $P=(v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n})\in V\times V\times \cdots \times V$ such that $v_{i}$ is adjacent to $v_{i+1}$ for $1\leq i<n$ .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Such a path P is called a path of length $n-1$ from $v_{1}$ to $v_{n}$ .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] These generalizations have significantly more efficient algorithms than the simplistic approach of running a single-pair shortest path algorithm on all relevant pairs of vertices.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Several well-known algorithms exist for solving this problem and its variants.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Additional algorithms and associated evaluations may be found in Cherkassky, Goldberg & Radzik (1996).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] An algorithm using topological sorting can solve the single-source shortest path problem in time Θ(*E* + *V*) in arbitrarily-weighted directed acyclic graphs.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The following table is taken from Schrijver (2004), with some corrections and additions.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] A green background indicates an asymptotically best bound in the table; *L* is the maximum length (or weight) among all edges, assuming integer edge weights.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Finds a negative cycle or calculates distances to all vertices.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest path problem finds the shortest paths between every pair of vertices v, v' in the graph.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest paths problem for unweighted directed graphs was introduced by Shimbel (1953), who observed that it could be solved by a linear number of matrix multiplications that takes a total time of *O*(*V*4).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Shortest path algorithms are applied to automatically find directions between physical locations, such as driving directions on web mapping websites like MapQuest or Google Maps.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] For this application fast specialized algorithms are available.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] For example, if vertices represent the states of a puzzle like a Rubik's Cube and each directed edge corresponds to a single move or turn, shortest path algorithms can be used to find a solution that uses the minimum possible number of moves.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] In a networking or telecommunications mindset, this shortest path problem is sometimes called the min-delay path problem and usually tied with a widest path problem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] For example, the algorithm may seek the shortest (min-delay) widest path, or widest shortest (min-delay) path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] A more lighthearted application is the games of "six degrees of separation" that try to find the shortest path in graphs like movie stars appearing in the same film.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Other applications, often studied in operations research, include plant and facility layout, robotics, transportation, and VLSI design.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] A road network can be considered as a graph with positive weights.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The nodes represent road junctions and each edge of the graph is associated with a road segment between two junctions.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The weight of an edge may correspond to the length of the associated road segment, the time needed to traverse the segment, or the cost of traversing the segment.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Using directed edges it is also possible to model one-way streets.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Such graphs are special in the sense that some edges are more important than others for long-distance travel (e.g. highways).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] This property has been formalized using the notion of highway dimension.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] There are a great number of algorithms that exploit this property and are therefore able to compute the shortest path a lot quicker than would be possible on general graphs.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] All of these algorithms work in two phases.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] In the first phase, the graph is preprocessed without knowing the source or target node.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] In this phase, source and target node are known.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The idea is that the road network is static, so the preprocessing phase can be done once and used for a large number of queries on the same road network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The algorithm with the fastest known query time is called hub labeling and is able to compute shortest path on the road networks of Europe or the US in a fraction of a microsecond.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] For shortest path problems in computational geometry, see Euclidean shortest path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The shortest multiple disconnected path is a representation of the primitive path network within the framework of Reptation theory.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The widest path problem seeks a path so that the minimum label of any edge is as large as possible.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Other related problems may be classified into the following categories.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Unlike the shortest path problem, which can be solved in polynomial time in graphs without negative cycles, shortest path problems which include additional constraints on the desired solution path are called Constrained Shortest Path First, and are harder to solve.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] One example is the constrained shortest path problem, which attempts to minimize the total cost of the path while at the same time maintaining another metric below a given threshold.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] This makes the problem NP-complete (such problems are not believed to be efficiently solvable for large sets of data, see P = NP problem).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Another NP-complete example requires a specific set of vertices to be included in the path, which makes the problem similar to the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The TSP is the problem of finding the shortest path that goes through every vertex exactly once, and returns to the start.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the longest path in a graph is also NP-complete.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The Canadian traveller problem and the stochastic shortest path problem are generalizations where either the graph is not completely known to the mover, changes over time, or where actions (traversals) are probabilistic.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Sometimes, the edges in a graph have personalities: each edge has its own selfish interest.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] An example is a communication network, in which each edge is a computer that possibly belongs to a different person.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Different computers have different transmission speeds, so every edge in the network has a numeric weight equal to the number of milliseconds it takes to transmit a message.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Our goal is to send a message between two points in the network in the shortest time possible.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] If we know the transmission-time of each computer (the weight of each edge), then we can use a standard shortest-paths algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] If we do not know the transmission times, then we have to ask each computer to tell us its transmission-time.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] But, the computers may be selfish: a computer might tell us that its transmission time is very long, so that we will not bother it with our messages.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] A possible solution to this problem is to use a variant of the VCG mechanism, which gives the computers an incentive to reveal their true weights.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] In some cases, the main goal is not to find the shortest path, but only to detect if the graph contains a negative cycle.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Many problems can be framed as a form of the shortest path for some suitably substituted notions of addition along a path and taking the minimum.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The general approach to these is to consider the two operations to be those of a semiring.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Semiring multiplication is done along the path, and the addition is between paths.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] This general framework is known as the algebraic path problem.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] Most of the classic shortest-path algorithms (and new ones) can be formulated as solving linear systems over such algebraic structures.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] More recently, an even more general framework for solving these (and much less obviously related problems) has been developed under the banner of valuation algebras.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] In real-life, a transportation network is usually stochastic and time-dependent.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The travel duration on a road segment depends on many factors such as the amount of traffic (origin-destination matrix), road work, weather, accidents and vehicle breakdowns.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] A more realistic model of such a road network is a stochastic time-dependent (STD) network.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] There is no accepted definition of optimal path under uncertainty (that is, in stochastic road networks).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] It is a controversial subject, despite considerable progress during the past decade.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] One common definition is a path with the minimum expected travel time.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The main advantage of this approach is that it can make use of efficient shortest path algorithms for deterministic networks.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] However, the resulting optimal path may not be reliable, because this approach fails to address travel time variability.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] To tackle this issue, some researchers use travel duration distribution instead of its expected value.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] So, they find the probability distribution of total travel duration using different optimization methods such as dynamic programming and Dijkstra's algorithm .
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] These methods use stochastic optimization, specifically stochastic dynamic programming to find the shortest path in networks with probabilistic arc length.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The terms *travel time reliability* and *travel time variability* are used as opposites in the transportation research literature: the higher the variability, the lower the reliability of predictions.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] To account for variability, researchers have suggested two alternative definitions for an optimal path under uncertainty.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] The *most reliable path* is one that maximizes the probability of arriving on time given a travel time budget.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/shortest-path-problem] An *α-reliable path* is one that minimizes the travel time budget required to arrive on time with a given probability.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] In theoretical computer science and network routing, **Suurballe's algorithm** is an algorithm for finding two disjoint paths in a nonnegatively-weighted directed graph, so that both paths connect the same pair of vertices and have minimum total length.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The main idea of Suurballe's algorithm is to use Dijkstra's algorithm to find one path, to modify the weights of the graph edges, and then to run Dijkstra's algorithm a second time.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The output of the algorithm is formed by combining these two paths, discarding edges that are traversed in opposite directions by the paths, and using the remaining edges to form the two paths to return as the output.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The modification to the weights is similar to the weight modification in Johnson's algorithm, and preserves the non-negativity of the weights while allowing the second instance of Dijkstra's algorithm to find the correct second path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The problem of finding two disjoint paths of minimum weight can be seen as a special case of a minimum cost flow problem, where in this case there are two units of "flow" and nodes have unit "capacity".
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Suurballe's algorithm, also, can be seen as a special case of a minimum cost flow algorithm that repeatedly pushes the maximum possible amount of flow along a shortest augmenting path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The first path found by Suurballe's algorithm is the shortest augmenting path for the initial (zero) flow, and the second path found by Suurballe's algorithm is the shortest augmenting path for the residual graph left after pushing one unit of flow along the first path.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Let *G* be a weighted directed graph with vertex set *V* and edge set *E* (figure A); let *s* be a designated source vertex in *G*, and let *t* be a designated destination vertex.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Let each edge (*u*,*v*) in *E*, from vertex *u* to vertex *v*, have a non-negative cost *w*(*u*,*v*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Define d(*s*,*u*) to be the cost of the shortest path to vertex *u* from vertex *s* in the shortest path tree rooted at *s* (figure C).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Note: Node and Vertex are often used interchangeably.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] According to the resulting modified cost function, all tree edges have a cost of 0, and non-tree edges have a non-negative cost.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Create a residual graph *Gt* formed from *G* by removing the edges of *G* on path *P*1 that are directed into *s* and then reverse the direction of the zero length edges along path *P*1 (figure D).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Find the shortest path *P*2 in the residual graph *Gt* by running Dijkstra's algorithm (figure E).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Discard the reversed edges of *P*2 from both paths.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The remaining edges of *P*1 and *P*2 form a subgraph with two outgoing edges at *s*, two incoming edges at *t*, and one incoming and one outgoing edge at each remaining vertex.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Therefore, this subgraph consists of two edge-disjoint paths from *s* to *t* and possibly some additional (zero-length) cycles.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Return the two disjoint paths from the subgraph.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The following example shows how Suurballe's algorithm finds the shortest pair of disjoint paths from *A* to *F*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Figure **A** illustrates a weighted graph *G*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Figure **C** illustrates the shortest path tree *T* rooted at *A*, and the computed distances from *A* to every vertex (*u*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Figure **D** shows the residual graph *Gt* with the updated cost of each edge and the edges of path *P*1 reversed.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Figure **F** illustrates both path *P*1 and path *P*2.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Figure **G** finds the shortest pair of disjoint paths by combining the edges of paths *P*1 and *P*2 and then discarding the common reversed edges between both paths (*B*–*D*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] As a result, we get the two shortest pair of disjoint paths (*A*–*B*–*E*–*F*) and (*A*–*C*–*D*–*F*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The weight of any path from s to t in the modified system of weights equals the weight in the original graph, minus d(*s*,*t*).
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Therefore, the shortest two disjoint paths under the modified weights are the same paths as the shortest two paths in the original graph, although they have different weights.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Suurballe's algorithm may be seen as a special case of the successive shortest paths method for finding a minimum cost flow with total flow amount two from s to t.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The modification to the weights does not affect the sequence of paths found by this method, only their weights.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Therefore, the correctness of the algorithm follows from the correctness of the successive shortest paths method.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] This algorithm requires two iterations of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Using Fibonacci heaps, both iterations can be performed in time $O(|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ where $|V|$ and $|E|$ are the number of vertices and edges respectively.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Therefore, the same time bound applies to Suurballe's algorithm.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The version of Suurballe's algorithm as described above finds paths that have disjoint edges, but that may share vertices.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] It is possible to use the same algorithm to find vertex-disjoint paths, by replacing each vertex by a pair of adjacent vertices, one with all of the incoming adjacencies *u-in* of the original vertex, and one with all of the outgoing adjacencies *u-out*.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Two edge-disjoint paths in this modified graph necessarily correspond to two vertex-disjoint paths in the original graph, and vice versa, so applying Suurballe's algorithm to the modified graph results in the construction of two vertex-disjoint paths in the original graph.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Suurballe's original 1974 algorithm was for the vertex-disjoint version of the problem, and was extended in 1984 by Suurballe and Tarjan to the edge-disjoint version.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] Note: The pair of adjacent vertices resulting from the split are connected by a zero cost uni-directional edge from the incoming to outgoing vertex.
[src:suurballe-disjoint-paths/suurballe-s-algorithm] The source vertex becomes *s-out* and the destination vertex becomes *t-in*.
